113.body: Recall from Chapter 4 that we want to check: P(x) = H(x) · T(x) Using pairings, we can check: e(P₁, G₂) = e(H₁, T₁) Problem : We need to encrypt the QAP polynomials! We need A(τ)·G₁, B(τ)·G₂, C(τ)·G₁ for each polynomial We need random values α, β, γ, δ to ensure soundness We need a random τ to evaluate polynomials at Solution : Run a trusted setup ceremony to generate these values!

115.body: Trusted setup generates random secrets that are used to encrypt the QAP: Secrets generated : α (alpha): Used for proof A component β (beta): Used for proof B and C components γ (gamma): Used for public input encryption δ (delta): Used for proof C component τ (tau): Random point to evaluate polynomials at Key properties : These secrets are random and unpredictable They MUST be deleted after the ceremony If leaked, anyone can forge proofs!
115.title: The Setup Ceremony

116.body: The secrets (α, β, γ, δ, τ) are called "toxic waste" because: Dangerous : If an attacker obtains them, they can forge proofs Must be destroyed : They should be securely deleted after the ceremony Unverifiable : We can't prove they were deleted (trust required!)
116.title: Toxic Waste

117.body:
The Powers of Tau is a structured reference string (SRS): [τ⁰·G₁, τ¹·G₁, τ²·G₁, ..., τⁿ·G₁]
[τ⁰·G₂, τ¹·G₂, τ²·G₂, ..., τⁿ·G₂] These powers of τ allow us to evaluate any polynomial at τ: P(x) = a₀ + a₁x + a₂x²
P(τ)·G₁ = a₀·τ⁰·G₁ + a₁·τ¹·G₁ + a₂·τ²·G₁ Key insight : We can compute P(τ)·G₁ without knowing τ!

#[derive(Clone, Debug)]
pub struct ProvingKey { /// α·G₁ (used in proof A component) pub alpha_g1: G1Affine, /// β·G₁ (used in proof A component) pub beta_g1: G1Affine, /// β·G₂ (used in verification) pub beta_g2: G2Affine, /// δ·G₁ (used in proof C component) pub delta_g1: G1Affine, /// δ·G₂ (used in verification) pub delta_g2: G2Affine, /// Encrypted A-polynomials: [α·Aᵢ(τ)·G₁] for i=0..m pub a_query: Vec<G1Affine>, /// Encrypted B-polynomials in G1: [β·Bᵢ(τ)·G₁] for i=0..m pub b_g1_query: Vec<G1Affine>, /// Encrypted B-polynomials in G2: [β·Bᵢ(τ)·G₂] for i=0..m pub b_g2_query: Vec<G2Affine>, /// Encrypted C-polynomials: [β·Cᵢ(τ)·G₁] for i=0..m pub c_query: Vec<G1Affine>, /// Encrypted division polynomials: [Hᵢ(τ)·G₁] for i=0..n-2 pub h_query: Vec<G1Affine>,
} Key components : alpha_g1, beta_g1, beta_g2, delta_g1, delta_g2 : Encrypted secrets a_query, b_g1_query, b_g2_query, c_query : Encrypted QAP polynomials h_query : Encrypted division polynomials (for H(x))

140.body:
The prover generates A, B, C to satisfy: A = [α]₁ + Σⱼ zⱼ·[Aⱼ(τ)]₁ + r·[δ]₁
B = [β]₂ + Σⱼ zⱼ·[Bⱼ(τ)]₂ + s·[δ]₂
C = Σⱼ zⱼ·[β·Aⱼ(τ) + α·Bⱼ(τ) + Cⱼ(τ)]₁ + [H(τ)]₁ + r·s·[δ]₁ - s·[β]₁ - r·[α]₁ Where: zⱼ are witness values r, s are random blinding factors [·]₁ means "encrypted in G₁" (··G₁) [·]₂ means "encrypted in G₂" (··G₂)
140.title: The Proof Equations

141.body:
The random values r and s ensure zero-knowledge: A = ... + r·δ
B = ... + s·δ
C = ... + r·s·δ - s·β - r·α Key insight : Different (r, s) values produce different-looking proofs for the same witness, preventing the verifier from learning anything about the witness.
141.title: Zero-Knowledge via Blinding

142.body: Recall from QAP that we check: P(x) = A(x) · B(x) - C(x) = H(x) · T(x) The prover computes H(x) = P(x) / T(x) and includes H(τ) in the C component. Why this works : If the witness is valid, P(x) is divisible by T(x) The prover can compute H(x) = P(x) / T(x) H(τ)·G₁ is included in the proof The verifier checks that H(x) exists (using the pairing equation)

161.body: A Groth16 proof is valid if and only if: e(A, B) = e(α, β) · e(Σ publicᵢ·ICᵢ, γ) · e(C, δ) Where: e(·, ·) is the bilinear pairing A, B, C are the proof components α, β, γ, δ are from the verification key ICᵢ are the input consistency elements publicᵢ are the public inputs
161.title: The Pairing Equation

162.body: Let's expand what each component means: Left side : e(A, B) = e(α·G₁ + A_witness + r·δ·G₁, β·G₂ + B_witness + s·δ·G₂) Right side : e(α, β) · e(Σ public·IC, γ) · e(C, δ) When the proof is correctly generated, these two sides are equal!
162.title: Expanding the Equation

163.body: The verification equation checks three things: Proof structure : A and B use the correct secrets (α, β, δ) Public input consistency : The witness matches the claimed public inputs QAP satisfaction : The division polynomial H(x) exists If any of these fail, the pairing equation won't hold!
163.title: Why This Works

164.body:
The term e(Σ publicᵢ·ICᵢ, γ) ensures public input consistency: IC[0] = β·G₁ (for the constant 1)
IC[i] = β·Aᵢ(τ)·G₁ for i = 1..num_inputs Σ publicᵢ·ICᵢ = public₀·IC[0] + public₁·IC[1] + ... = 1·β·G₁ + c·β·A₁(τ)·G₁ = β·(1 + c·A₁(τ))·G₁ This ensures the witness used the correct public inputs!

3.body: Think of the "Where's Waldo?" puzzle: You find Waldo quickly. You want to prove to your friend you found him, but you don't want to reveal his location (spoiling the fun). Zero-knowledge solution : You (prover) find Waldo You cover the page with a large piece of cardboard with a small cutout You position the cutout over Waldo so only Waldo is visible Your friend (verifier) sees Waldo through the hole Your friend is convinced Waldo exists on the page But your friend learns nothing about Waldo's location! This captures the three properties of zero-knowledge proofs: Completeness : If Waldo is really there, your friend will be convinced Soundness : If Waldo isn't there, you can't fake the proof Zero-knowledge : Your friend learns only that Waldo exists, not where

31.body: Polynomials are incredibly useful in zero-knowledge proofs because of this fundamental theorem : Theorem : A degree-d polynomial is uniquely determined by d+1 points. 33.body:
Interpolation is the reverse of evaluation: given points, find the polynomial. Lagrange Interpolation finds the unique polynomial passing through given points: Given: (1, 3), (2, 5), (3, 9)
Find: P(x) such that P(1)=3, P(2)=5, P(3)=9 Formula : For points (x₁, y₁), ..., (xₙ, yₙ): P(x) = Σ yᵢ · Lᵢ(x) Where Lᵢ(x) is the i-th Lagrange basis polynomial: Lᵢ(x) = Π (x - xⱼ) / (xᵢ - xⱼ) for all j ≠ i Example (simplified): Given points (1, 3), (2, 5): L₁(x) = (x - 2) / (1 - 2) = (x - 2) / -1 = 2 - x
L₂(x) = (x - 1) / (2 - 1) = (x - 1) / 1 = x - 1 P(x) = 3·L₁(x) + 5·L₂(x) = 3(2 - x) + 5(x - 1) = 6 - 3x + 5x - 5 = 1 + 2x Verify: P(1) = 1 + 2(1) = 3 ✓ P(2) = 1 + 2(2) = 5 ✓

36.body: A key insight in Groth16: A polynomial is divisible by another if and only if it evaluates to zero at all roots of the divisor . Example : Let T(x) = (x - 1)(x - 2)(x - 3) (a "target polynomial") If P(x) = H(x) · T(x), then: P(1) = H(1) · T(1) = H(1) · 0 = 0 P(2) = H(2) · T(2) = H(2) · 0 = 0 P(3) = H(3) · T(3) = H(3) · 0 = 0 Converse : If P(1) = P(2) = P(3) = 0, then P(x) is divisible by T(x)! This is the QAP satisfaction check in Groth16!

47.body: R1CS (Rank-1 Constraint System) is a way to represent computations as quadratic constraints. It's the standard input format for modern zk-SNARK systems like Groth16. Key idea : Any computation can be broken down into a sequence of multiplications and additions, where each multiplication is a constraint.

48.body: An R1CS constraint has the form: Az ∘ Bz = Cz Where: A, B, C are matrices (vectors for a single constraint) z is the witness vector (assignment to all variables) ∘ denotes element-wise multiplication The equation must hold for each row (constraint) For a single constraint : A, B, C are vectors (not matrices) z is the witness vector We check: <A, z> · <B, z> = <C, z> (dot products)

49.body: The witness z contains all values in the computation: z = [1, public_outputs..., private_inputs...] The 1 at the beginning is a constant (for convenience in encoding constant terms). Example for a × b = c : z = [1, c, a, b] = [1, 12, 3, 4]

Let's convert a × b = c to R1CS step by step: Step 1: Identify variables z = [1, c, a, b] [0, 1, 2, 3] ← indices Step 2: Create constraint vectors We want: a × b = c We need three vectors A, B, C such that: <A, z> · <B, z> = <C, z> The solution: A = [0, 0, 1, 0] ← selects 'a' (index 2)
B = [0, 0, 0, 1] ← selects 'b' (index 3)
C = [0, 1, 0, 0] ← selects 'c' (index 1) Step 3: Verify the constraint Compute each dot product: <A, z> = 0·1 + 0·c + 1·a + 0·b = a
<B, z> = 0·1 + 0·c + 0·a + 1·b = b
<C, z> = 0·1 + 1·c + 0·a + 0·b = c Check the constraint: <A, z> · <B, z> = a · b
<C, z> = c Verify: a · b = c ✓ With concrete numbers (a=3, b=4, c=12): <A, z> = 0·1 + 0·12 + 1·3 + 0·4 = 3
<B, z> = 0·1 + 0·12 + 0·3 + 1·4 = 4
<C, z> = 0·1 + 1·12 + 0·3 + 0·4 = 12 Check: 3 · 4 = 12 ✓

69.body: QAP (Quadratic Arithmetic Program) is a transformation that converts R1CS constraints into polynomial equations. Instead of checking n constraints separately, we check if one polynomial divides another. Key insight : Polynomial divisibility at specific points (1, 2, ..., n) is equivalent to satisfying n R1CS constraints!

71.body: The target polynomial is: T(x) = (x - 1)(x - 2)...(x - n) Where n is the number of constraints. Key property : T(x) has roots exactly at x = 1, 2, ..., n (the constraint indices).

72.body: Given a witness z = [z₀, z₁, ..., zₘ], we: Compute A(x) = Σⱼ zⱼ · Aⱼ(x) Compute B(x) = Σⱼ zⱼ · Bⱼ(x) Compute C(x) = Σⱼ zⱼ · Cⱼ(x) Compute P(x) = A(x) · B(x) - C(x) Check if P(x) is divisible by T(x) Why this works : P(i) = A(i) · B(i) - C(i) for i = 1, ..., n If the witness satisfies constraint i, then P(i) = 0 If P(i) = 0 for all i = 1, ..., n, then T(x) divides P(x) Checking one polynomial division is faster than checking n constraints!

73.body:
To construct Aⱼ(x), Bⱼ(x), Cⱼ(x), we use Lagrange interpolation : Given points (x₁, y₁), (x₂, y₂), ..., (xₙ, yₙ), the unique polynomial passing through them is: P(x) = Σᵢ yᵢ · Lᵢ(x) Where Lᵢ(x) is the i-th Lagrange basis polynomial: Lᵢ(x) = Πⱼ≠ᵢ (x - xⱼ) / (xᵢ - xⱼ) Example : Points (1, 2), (2, 4) L₁(x) = (x - 2) / (1 - 2) = 2 - x
L₂(x) = (x - 1) / (2 - 1) = x - 1 P(x) = 2·L₁(x) + 4·L₂(x) = 2(2 - x) + 4(x - 1) = 4 - 2x + 4x - 4 = 2x Verify: P(1) = 2 ✓, P(2) = 4 ✓

{ if num_constraints == 0 { return Polynomial::<F>::new(vec![]); } // Start with (x - 1) let mut result = Polynomial::<F>::new(vec![ FieldWrapper::<F>::zero() - FieldWrapper::<F>::one(), // -1 FieldWrapper::<F>::one(), // x ]); // Multiply by (x - i) for i = 2..num_constraints for i in 2..=num_constraints { let i_field = FieldWrapper::<F>::from(i as u64); let factor = Polynomial::<F>::new(vec![ FieldWrapper::<F>::zero() - i_field, // -i FieldWrapper::<F>::one(), // x ]); result = result * factor; } result

87.body: In QAP, we want to verify: P(x) = H(x) · T(x) Problem : If we reveal P(x) and H(x), we leak information about the witness! Solution with pairings : Check the equation in the exponent : e(P₁, G₂) = e(H₁, T₁) Where: P₁ = P(x) · G₁ (P encrypted in G₁) H₁ = H(x) · G₁ (H encrypted in G₁) T₁ = T(x) · G₁ (T encrypted in G₁) e(·, ·) is the bilinear pairing The verifier can check the equation without learning P(x), H(x), or the witness!

90.body: Elliptic curves form an abelian group under the "chord-and-tangent" addition: Addition (P + Q = R) : Draw a line through P and Q Find the third intersection with the curve Reflect across the x-axis Doubling (P + P = 2P) : Draw the tangent line at P Find the second intersection with the curve Reflect across the x-axis Scalar multiplication (k·P) : k·P = P + P + ... + P (k times) This can be computed efficiently using the "double-and-add" algorithm (O(log k) time).

91.body: In pairing-based cryptography, we use two groups : G₁ : Points on the curve over the base field 𝔽ₚ Smaller elements (more efficient) Used for elements that need to be compared/combined G₂ : Points on the curve over an extension field 𝔽ₚ² Larger elements (less efficient) Used for pairing targets Both groups have the same order (number of elements): a large prime r.

93.body: A bilinear pairing is a function: e: G₁ × G₂ → Gₜ Where Gₜ is a target group (usually 𝔽ₚⁿ). Key properties : Bilinearity : e(a·P, b·Q) = e(P, Q)ᵃ·ᵇ = e(a·P, Q)ᵇ = e(P, b·Q)ᵃ Non-degeneracy : If e(P, Q) = 1 for all Q, then P = ∞ Computability : e(P, Q) can be computed efficiently

94.body:
The pairing enables us to check equations in the exponent : Integer equation : a = b Pairing check : e(a·G₁, G₂) = e(b·G₁, G₂) This works because: e(a·G₁, G₂) = e(G₁, G₂)ᵃ
e(b·G₁, G₂) = e(G₁, G₂)ᵇ If a = b, then e(G₁, G₂)ᵃ = e(G₁, G₂)ᵇ
